This is a bracket that perches on a 3/4-inch plywood board and holds two NEMA 17 stepper motors side by side.
I designed this for use on a drawbot I'm building - I decided to center the motors to simplify wiring. I'll just place two pulleys at the top edges of the plywood where the motors would normally go.
The shape is optimized for printing on a Makerbot Replicator.

The piece is saved in a position that is optimized for printing - you should be able to load the STL into replicatorg, generate gcode (I'd recommend at least 20% infill), and print. UPDATE: The bracket fits well (you'll probably want to use the screw-holes to really secure it to the plywood), but the circular indentation around the shaft might not fit every NEMA 17 motor - I'm about to upload a version (filename has "no_indent" in it) without that feature. I'm also attaching some photos of the drawbot so far - I'm using two of LoialOtter's pulleys (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:26295) and two of these awesome pulleys from Electronics Goldmine (http://www.goldmine-elec-products.com/prodinfo.asp?number=G16273).

title: MakerWare Profiles for Polycarbonate on an R2x

description.text:
Here are some MakerWare profiles that I have been using with Polycarbonate on a Replicator 2x. PC is:
  • Crystal-clear like T-glase
  • About twice as strong and tough as ABS, but stiffer than Nylon
  • Suitable for mechanical use up to ~150C
  • Prone to warping like ABS
    • THIS IS EXPERIMENTAL. YOU CAN BREAK YOUR PRINTER. USE AT YOUR OWN RISK. READ THE INSTRUCTIONS TO SEE MY HARDWARE SETUP BEFORE ATTEMPTING. Details and pics here:
    https://groups.google.com/forum/#!topic/makerbot/sDLkvrXNFK8 I have attached the vase STL for the pictured print because Thingiverse requires a model to be attached to Things, apparently. The original is here: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:31722

PC requires printing temps that are WAY too hot for the stock R2x parts. PC should only printed with a high-temp setup, preferably all-metal. You can probably use the stock R2x hot end as long as the injection-molded carriage is replaced. IT WILL WARP from sustained high-temp printing. The stock Superstruder is a "maybe." If you keep your build chamber cool and do prints without a lot of retraction, you can probably stick with it. I used:
  • Carl's T-shaped heater block, threaded thermal barrier, cooling bar, and aluminum dual carriage http://shop.raffle.ch/
  • DHeadrick's aluminum 3in1 extruder http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:136423
  • 0.5mm nozzle from QU-BD (to get the nozzle viscosity down)
  • Stock R2x heated build plate
    • Basic print settings:
  • 0.5mm layer width, 0.3mm layer height (bigger extruded threads provide better visual clarity and require less force to extrude)
  • 265C nozzle temp
  • 130C HBP temp, on UHU gluestick for good results. Poor results on 5 mil Kapton with ABS slurry. Bare Kapton or phenolic-type plates such as Garolite / G10 WILL NOT stick
  • 30-60 mm/s print speed due to high PC viscosity and large nozzle (= higher plastic flow rate)
    • PC warps worse than ABS because of the high glass point and high coefficient of thermal expansion. Parts should be designed with warping prevention in mind, just like large ABS prints. Tram close to the bed for good adhesion. Use skirts and helper discs on sharp corners, and reduce infill if you need to decrease warping stresses. Note that molten PC is very sticky and likes to gob up on the nozzle if you're over-extruding. Pull excess PC off the outside of the nozzle with tweezers immediately before printing. You should dial in your print settings using a 100% infill calibration cube. Get the filament diameter, feedstockMultiplier (packing density), and build plate adhesion sorted on the calibration cube before attempting any real prints. Otherwise you'll probably end up with a giant ball of indestructible plastic stuck to your nozzle. This stuff is STRONG and can't be conveniently dissolved by solvents like ABS can.

description.text: The cleaned up scan and the original scan data are included.

To the aspiring troll, the original locking box had one basic design flaw: once closed, it could be re-opened. In this version, I have fixed that design flaw, allowing for increased awesome in applications involving high-amplitude, audio-waveform-generation-based lulz. Alternatively, you can hand it to your really clever friends and claim that it's a Japanese puzzle box. Or waterproof it, put some awesome stuff in it, and bury it in the back yard as a time capsule. Really, the sky's the limit! I've also added an alternate lid if you would like your box to be a piggy bank. If you want your money back out of it, you'll have to smash it. Just like the good old days!

1: Print.
2: Be careful. Once this is closed, it is CLOSED.
3: Insert object which you would like to be permanently sealed.
4: Close box.
5: ???
6: PROFIT! Also, if you'd like to do some testing, please tell me in the comments what your results were. So far I've made two of the totally sealed boxes, and the first one the tabs broke trying to close the box. The second one a coworker threw as hard as he could into a concrete wall twice, and on the second throw the lid popped off. Again, the problem was that one of the tabs broke. In v2 I am going to add some beefier tabs, and this box should present a real challenge for anyone wanting to get into it.

Just a simple sorting box with various shelfs. The walls are optimized for minimal material usage and at the same time stable. They are 1.6mm thick, so optimal for 0.4mm nozzles

Yes, I know, picket fences are supposed to be white, but my wife wants red, nuff said.
Unlike bought, when the dog breaks it playing footie, you just print new bits :-)

fence.scad is the main OpenSCAD file, components are held together with M6 threads supplied by ISOThread.scad. see photo of assembled unit on glass table.
'Panels' are the flat panels bolted together with 4 holes in each panel.
Photo shows an assembly that stretches to 4 feet (approx 120 cm), it contains 36 'panels', 2 sets of 'end panels' (2 & 3 hole panels for ends), joined together by 78 bolts and 70 nuts, supported by 4 'top posts' and 4 'bottom posts'. uncommenting "\panels();" line in fence.scad will allow creation of a .stl containing panels, num variable sets how many panels are included.
Attached panels.stl is pre-compiled containing 8 panels. uncommenting "\nuts();" line in fence.scad will allow creation of a .stl containing nuts, num variable sets how many nuts are included.
Attached nuts.stl is pre-compiled containing 16 nuts.
  • bolts(); gets stl for bolts, bolts.stl contains 16 bolts.
  • ends(); gets stl containing 2 sets of end panels, ends.stl cointains 2 sets of end panels.
  • toppost(); gets stl for a single top post (contains threads to allow fence to be bolted to it), toppost.stl contains a top post.
  • botpost(); gets stl for single bottom post (spike to drive into ground), botpost.stl contains 1 bottom post.
    • Oddities:
    I have a problem printing PLA, damned stuff sticks so bad that I damage parts removing them, even when stone cold, so panels are printed on their edge.
    Bolts and nuts are not that great, but that seems to be an advantage, can just push on the tighten slightly.
    Top post has a built in slider, bottom skirt can mean this has to be broken out after printing, the slider allows the fence to be expanded / condensed whilst attached to post.
    Top post has an internal thread at bottom for joining to spike and an external thread at top to allow stacking (not shown in photos). All parts build without added supports.

A small, detailed, print to test ability of printer to retract (not print) between towers of varying widths and matching gaps, as well as to print a thin layer that does span the tops of all the towers in X & Y.  
I discovered that my printer (Portabee) stopped printing when Cura had 'retract' enabled!  (This print is with retract disabled.)  
Filament feed/retract was observed to be random amounts (both feed distance and retract distance!) with retract enabled.  Feed stepper needs to be investigated / repaired.  
Follow up:  retraction speed slowed, retraction distance reduced, grip on extruder loosened (avoid shredding)...  retract now works!

comments.text:
The latest version of Cura 14.06.1 is doing much better at retractions now, it has more adjustable parameters than previous versions.
I use Slic3r too for more complex and tricky prints, Slic3r is fantastic and has a butload of parameters, but Cura is much faster at slicing and its doing a pretty decent job (but not outstanding).
See my prints of this Thing sliced with Cura 14.06.1 with several retraction length and retraction speed values.
Print #1 - no retraction at all - 100 microns layer height - 20 mm/s outer perimeter speed - 60 mm/s move - 2 grams - 28 minutes - ABS
Print #2 - retraction 2mm at 16 mm/s - 100 microns layer - 20 mm/s outer perimeter speed - 60 mm/s move - 2 grams - 30 minutes - ABS
Print #3 - retraction 4mm at 8 mm/s - 100 microns layer - 20 mm/s outer perimeter speed - 60 mm/s move - 2 grams - 38 minutes - ABS
Print #4 - retraction 6mm at 8 mm/s - 100 microns layer - 20 mm/s outer perimeter speed - 60 mm/s move - 2 grams - 43 minutes - ABS

title: Post and beam cape for sale in Wilton, Maine.

description.text:
This is a model of a 3 bedroom home my company had for sale in Wilton, Maine. The model is quite accurate, right down to the window grids.
The only inaccuracy would be the wrong # of columns supporting the deck. I don't know how I missed this.

I modeled it using Sketchup, using the photo-matching feature. I printed it on a Printrbot LC, using default setting in Repetier. I did find that the deck fails without using support material. To get around this, I paused the print before the decking was laid (after the columns though), and I folded a paper/cardstock box, and placed in between the house and columns to serve as a temp bridge for the decking. It worked like a charm.
